Sakagura, brought to you by TIC Group of Cha-An, Sobaya, Shabu-Tatsu and Decibel just to name a few, is tucked away where no one would expect a sake bar to exist-in the basement of a high-rise office building. Actually such subterranean establishments are pretty common in Japan, and once you step inside Sakagura, you'll feel like drinking chilled rice wine, accompanied by traditional izakaya fare, like many "salary men" do in the Land of the Rising Sun. The menu is vast, so prepare to be overwhelmed-with around fifty dishes and over 200 bottles of sake to choose from, it may be wise to study their menu a bit beforehand. Contrary to some reviews of Sakagura floating around on the 'net, the servers are literally just "servers"-their poor English speaking skills won't get you far in the recommendations department. But as long as you're not a picky eater, you can't go wrong with just blind-picking here, as most of the dishes are as good as they get in New York City. If you're dining with a significant other, don't get stingy-choose four or five items to share. Admittedly, a place like Sakagura is hard to review as the food menu seems to be all over the place and is reminiscent of eating at a Chinese restaurant without having a f*cking clue as to what you're ordering. However, what makes this place stand out among the plethora of izakayas in the City is that none of the dozen or so dishes we tried tasted bad. That kind of consistency in any bar's kitchen is rare and highly applaudable. Furthermore, Sakagura's expansive sake selection will encourage many repeated visits, especially for those seeking cold drinks during the hot months of summer who are either a.) sick of drinking white wine or b.) feel their sexuality is on the line when ordering glasses of rose. This sake bar is not without quibbles though-short operating hours and its desolate location almost guarantee a quick end to your night out. Perhaps Sakagura is the perfect place to have a blind date-if things start getting weird, you can always ask for the check and go home right away, without the guilt of not having taken your date elsewhere. One Drink Ahead
