I've never been to Japan before. This is a saddening confession, but upon stepping into the basement of 211 E. 43rd Street, I think I've gotten as close to Japan as I'll ever be. First, a disclaimer: Yes, the journey to this restaurant is somewhat confusing. You may be tempted to turn around and head back, daunted by the dark passageway and the lack of signage. Don't. I called a few days beforehand to make a reservation for my group of four. Yes, I realize that there's an OpenTable option, but I've never had much success with it. Call ahead, earlier if possible, to secure your seats. Thus, my friends and I came here on Tuesday night for our planned dinner. We were seated in the midst of the main room, where we could see Japanese businessmen conversing in a booth, a few couples seated near the bar that was well-stocked with sake and other forms of alcohol. With the ambiance, the wooden tables set with chopsticks in front of us, and the ceiling dotted with dim lights, It felt like we had been transported to the other side of the world. The menu is, without a doubt, overwhelming. We stuck to some of the classics and between the four us, selected six dishes total. Our waitress was helpful in explaining some of the plates we weren't sure about and throughout the night, she checked up on us several times to make sure we had gotten what we had ordered as well as refilling our glasses. The only downside to the service was that it seemed that our plates came out haphazardly and too close together; I would have appreciated if they'd spaced them out a bit more. But onto the important part: the food. The Buta Kakuni was a definite must-order; the sizable piece of pork belly came in a small bowl and was as soft and tender as tofu; a true melt-in-your-mouth dish. We also ordered the Agedashi Tofu; three slices of tofu that had a slightly crisp-fried skin in a soy sauce-flavored broth. There were several bonito flakes scattered on top as well, and though it was a simple dish, the flavor really came through. We also had the Tori Karaage, which I thoroughly enjoyed; after all, who doesn't like deep-fried chicken? Finally, the onigiri were surprisingly savory for being what they were; I had the spicy salmon cod roe, and the addition of the nori and pickles that it was served with made for a great balance. There were some dishes that I didn't quite appreciate as much though. The Yuba Shumai also seemed delicious on paper, though was slightly disappointing in real life; they were more like meatballs than the shumai I was used to, and lacked any special flavor despite being dipped in the accompanying sauce. The Sanshoku Nasu Dengaku consisted of six small pieces of eggplant with sauces on each; I didn't really get to enjoy the flavor or texture of this dish either. I have experienced here a problem I have found at numerous other tapas or "small plates" restaurants; the portion to price ratio may not be worth it for everyone. I paid about $20 for my portion of the meal and felt like I could still have used another plate or two of food. Nonetheless, I had a wonderful dinner here and a greater appreciation of Japanese cuisine.
